00:55.350 --> 00:57.960
<i>My name is Anthony Powell.</i>

00:58.438 --> 01:01.906
<i>I grew up on this dairy farm
in Taranaki, New Zealand.</i>

01:01.908 --> 01:03.575
<i>But I've actually spent most</i>

01:03.577 --> 01:07.745
<i>of my adult life living
and working in Antarctica.</i>

01:07.747 --> 01:10.415
<i>The most common question
I get asked is</i>

01:10.417 --> 01:12.650
<i>"What's it like to live
down there?"</i>

01:13.686 --> 01:16.287
<i>It's so hard to answer
that in words</i>

01:16.289 --> 01:19.457
<i>and it's never really been
captured on film before.</i>

01:20.459 --> 01:23.628
<i>But there's something about
time lapse photography</i>

01:23.630 --> 01:27.565
<i>that brings to life
the dynamic forces of nature</i>

01:27.567 --> 01:29.968
<i>that you can feel
and sense around you,</i>

01:29.970 --> 01:32.437
<i>but you can't actually see.</i>

01:33.806 --> 01:37.575
<i>So I've taught myself how
to use a variety of cameras</i>

01:37.577 --> 01:40.778
<i>and built some homemade
equipment in my spare time</i>

01:40.780 --> 01:43.781
<i>that can still function
in the extreme cold.</i>

02:27.327 --> 02:31.597
<i>It's taken me more than
10 years to make this film.</i>

02:31.599 --> 02:33.432
<i>I've worn out
thousands of dollars</i>

02:33.434 --> 02:34.867
<i>worth of camera gear...</i>

02:36.503 --> 02:39.972
<i>and spent countless hours
standing in the freezing cold</i>

02:39.974 --> 02:43.976
<i>in an effort to capture
the true feeling of this vast</i>

02:43.978 --> 02:45.344
<i>important place.</i>

02:49.716 --> 02:53.018
<i>There really are only
two seasons in Antarctica:</i>

02:53.020 --> 02:56.088
<i>a busy summer when most
of the science happens...</i>

02:59.025 --> 03:01.026
<i>and a wild and lonely winter</i>

03:01.028 --> 03:03.462
<i>that few people will
ever experience.</i>

03:09.636 --> 03:11.804
<i>To understand the place properly</i>

03:11.806 --> 03:14.573
<i>you really need to spend
one full year</i>

03:14.575 --> 03:16.642
<i>down here on the ice.</i>

05:06.955 --> 05:08.789
<i>I think that most people</i>

05:08.791 --> 05:11.158
<i>think that we're all scientists.</i>

05:11.160 --> 05:14.061
<i>There are real people
down here.</i>

05:14.063 --> 05:16.597
<i>It's not just
the people you see</i>

05:16.599 --> 05:18.566
<i>on the National Geographic
channels</i>

05:18.568 --> 05:21.535
<i>or it's not people
who can afford</i>

05:21.537 --> 05:23.604
<i>a $10.000 cruise.</i>

05:25.574 --> 05:28.142
<i>It's people who are just
like you and me</i>

05:28.144 --> 05:30.878
<i>who are average citizens</i>

05:30.946 --> 05:32.947
<i>who are working and doing a job</i>

06:26.668 --> 06:28.168
<i>That first breath...</i>

06:28.170 --> 06:30.070
<i>it's like a sledgehammer
to the face.</i>

06:30.972 --> 06:32.740
<i>It's your wake up call.</i>

06:32.742 --> 06:33.974
<i>It's okay, you're here now.</i>

06:33.976 --> 06:35.743
<i>This is the real deal.</i>

06:45.855 --> 06:47.221
<i>I couldn't believe
I was actually doing it.</i>

06:47.223 --> 06:48.222
<i>I was actually here.</i>

06:48.224 --> 06:49.657
<i>I was in Antarctica...</i>

06:49.659 --> 06:50.891
<i>the bottom of the planet.</i>

06:50.893 --> 06:52.826
<i>And then my second thought was</i>

06:52.828 --> 06:55.930
"Oh crap,
what have I just done?"

06:55.932 --> 06:57.197
Why am I here?

07:09.946 --> 07:11.713
<i>I saw Erebus</i>

07:11.715 --> 07:13.782
<i>and wanted to go
hiking there</i>

07:13.784 --> 07:14.783
<i>and snowboard down it</i>

07:14.785 --> 07:16.251
and I was quickly told "No"

07:16.253 --> 07:18.219
and then I was off to work.

07:27.363 --> 07:29.898
<i>We had been thinking
oh we're going to Antarctica</i>

07:29.900 --> 07:32.767
<i>and when you get here it's like,
oh yeah I've gotta work</i>

07:32.769 --> 07:35.070
<i>And you don't put that
into your head your first time</i>

07:35.072 --> 07:37.606
<i>you're so excited
about coming down</i>

07:37.608 --> 07:40.775
that you forget that you're
coming down here for a reason.

07:43.746 --> 07:45.380
<i>They hurried us off the plane</i>

07:45.382 --> 07:47.349
<i>so we couldn't take
a look around</i>

07:47.351 --> 07:49.684
<i>and pretty much
it was just here</i>

07:49.686 --> 07:51.786
<i>and the next thing we knew
we were in town.</i>

07:54.157 --> 07:57.125
<i>So the first thing we really saw
of Antarctica was McMurdo</i>

07:57.127 --> 07:59.327
and that's always kind of
disappointing sometimes.

08:15.111 --> 08:16.911
<i>It's a pretty small,
tight community</i>

08:16.979 --> 08:19.214
<i>People pull together
and get things done.</i>

08:19.216 --> 08:23.018
<i>Pretty amazing what gets done
for what little we have.</i>

08:23.020 --> 08:25.687
I've seen a lot of different
personalities come down here.

08:25.689 --> 08:28.857
The ones that seem to do
the most of it are

08:28.859 --> 08:32.027
the die-hards or
the more grounded people.

08:37.732 --> 08:41.803
<i>McMurdo Station sits
beside the sea on Ross Island.</i>

08:41.804 --> 08:44.072
<i>It's dwarfed by Mt. Erebus</i>

08:44.073 --> 08:48.009
<i>the southernmost
active volcano in the world.</i>

08:48.011 --> 08:51.346
<i>Three kilometers away on
the other side of the peninsula</i>

08:51.348 --> 08:53.348
<i>is the small New Zealand outpost</i>

08:53.350 --> 08:55.383
<i>Scott Base.</i>

08:57.420 --> 09:00.055
<i>Scott Base is a lot
more typical in size</i>

09:00.057 --> 09:03.259
<i>of the other bases
dotted around Antarctica.</i>

09:06.063 --> 09:08.964
<i>And its proximity
to McMurdo is unusual.</i>

09:15.205 --> 09:18.140
<i>There are only
30 permanently manned bases</i>

09:18.142 --> 09:21.010
<i>on the entire continent
and most of these</i>

09:21.012 --> 09:24.146
<i>have less than 20 people
living in them in the winter.</i>

09:29.886 --> 09:33.256
<i>At Scott Base you have to
live and work in one building.</i>

09:33.258 --> 09:36.326
<i>Our accommodation
is a very small room</i>

09:36.328 --> 09:38.395
<i>It's like a cell,
if you like,</i>

09:38.397 --> 09:40.230
<i>or a cupboard.</i>

09:46.104 --> 09:50.440
<i>A lot of things here
can get to you pretty quickly</i>

09:50.442 --> 09:52.075
<i>especially in winter.</i>

09:54.112 --> 09:56.113
<i>And you cannot change them.</i>

09:57.281 --> 10:00.016
You cannot argue much
about them either

10:00.018 --> 10:03.053
because this person
will be in front of your eyes,

10:03.055 --> 10:05.088
you know, on the next Smoko.

10:05.890 --> 10:09.392
<i>So to be tolerant
is very important.</i>

10:16.168 --> 10:17.434
<i>When people ask me why</i>

10:17.436 --> 10:22.839
to come back because this
is the second time

10:22.841 --> 10:24.174
I've arrived in Antarctica.

10:24.176 --> 10:25.876
<i>For me it's those
white mountains.</i>

10:27.044 --> 10:29.045
<i>Those white mountains</i>

10:29.047 --> 10:30.380
<i>and you look across
and you know</i>

10:30.382 --> 10:32.783
<i>just because
humanity had trouble</i>

10:32.785 --> 10:35.886
<i>getting here in the first place
we're relatively new arrivals.</i>

10:35.888 --> 10:39.055
<i>We have not had the opportunity
to mess it up very much yet.</i>

10:45.497 --> 10:48.532
We have nations getting along
better in Antarctica

10:48.534 --> 10:51.535
than I think they're doing
anywhere else in the world.

10:51.537 --> 10:53.537
It's worth something
to keep it this way

10:53.539 --> 10:56.339
<i>if we can do whatever we can
to keep the co-operations</i>

10:56.341 --> 10:58.074
<i>and just the pure pursuit
of things</i>

10:58.076 --> 10:59.843
<i>that make us
better as humans.</i>

11:01.145 --> 11:02.345
<i>That's happening right now</i>

11:02.347 --> 11:04.815
<i>on this continent,
and it's special.</i>

11:12.123 --> 11:14.224
<i>I could live indefinitely here</i>

11:14.226 --> 11:16.092
if I could, on occasion,

11:17.829 --> 11:18.895
get out.

11:18.897 --> 11:19.896
Like I haven't...

11:19.898 --> 11:22.032
I've literally gone nowhere

11:22.034 --> 11:23.400
since August.

11:24.936 --> 11:26.436
<i>Most people that have
been here that long</i>

11:26.438 --> 11:28.438
<i>at least have gone to maybe</i>

11:28.440 --> 11:30.106
<i>the Pole or something...</i>

11:30.875 --> 11:32.409
<i>or at least gotten out of town.</i>

11:38.916 --> 11:41.084
<i>You will get to see
some fun stuff</i>

11:41.086 --> 11:44.554
<i>but the main thing you're
down here for is to work.</i>

11:44.556 --> 11:46.857
<i>And I hate to sound cold</i>

11:46.859 --> 11:47.891
<i>when it comes to that,</i>

11:47.893 --> 11:49.593
<i>but I think a lot of people
lose that focus</i>

11:49.595 --> 11:51.094
and when they come down here

11:51.096 --> 11:53.196
and all they get to see
is a dish room

11:53.198 --> 11:56.466
or get to stare at
a computer the whole time

11:56.468 --> 11:57.934
I think they might be
a little disillusioned.

12:08.947 --> 12:11.582
<i>I came down with
the Italians originally.</i>

12:12.384 --> 12:14.352
But having done it once

12:14.354 --> 12:17.054
you know I sort of thought
well that'll do.

12:17.056 --> 12:18.055
But a couple of years later

12:18.057 --> 12:18.956
I was back again.

12:20.592 --> 12:21.626
<i>Still here.</i>

12:24.263 --> 12:27.632
<i>Rob has been flying
in Antarctica for 20 years,</i>

12:27.634 --> 12:29.467
<i>but he's never done
a winter here.</i>

12:29.469 --> 12:31.903
<i>Helicopters only fly
in the summer.</i>

12:38.277 --> 12:41.279
<i>It's probably safer flying here
than in New Zealand</i>

12:41.281 --> 12:44.482
<i>because you never have
to contend with the weather.</i>

12:44.484 --> 12:47.351
<i>At home there's various
degrees of weather.</i>

12:47.353 --> 12:49.287
Here it's either good
or it's not.

12:49.289 --> 12:51.555
Whereas home,
it might be okay

12:51.557 --> 12:53.057
or just okay

12:53.059 --> 12:54.458
or I think I can make it.

12:54.460 --> 12:56.060
But there's none of that here.

13:04.369 --> 13:08.472
<i>So, what would be
your favorite place to fly to?</i>

13:09.174 --> 13:10.508
Christchurch.

13:14.047 --> 13:15.613
No, I like the Dry Valleys.

13:15.615 --> 13:18.716
I like the Upper Wright
and the Beacon Valley as well.

13:18.718 --> 13:20.952
It's spectacular scenery,
it really is.

13:27.293 --> 13:30.227
Like Rob, I'm one
of the lucky ones.

13:30.229 --> 13:32.129
<i>The work I do in Antarctica</i>

13:32.131 --> 13:34.165
<i>allows me to get out
and experience</i>

13:34.167 --> 13:36.600
<i>some of the grandeur
and vast emptiness</i>

13:36.602 --> 13:38.502
<i>of this amazing continent.</i>

14:09.534 --> 14:12.403
<i>Wherever there is research
happening in the field</i>

14:12.405 --> 14:14.538
<i>they need their
communications support.</i>

14:14.540 --> 14:16.307
<i>So I spend a lot of time</i>

14:16.309 --> 14:18.075
<i>setting up radio equipment</i>

14:18.077 --> 14:19.610
<i>in remote locations.</i>

14:31.358 --> 14:34.127
<i>When I first came down
here in 1998,</i>

14:34.129 --> 14:38.564
<i>I was struck by how
pure and untouched it was.</i>

14:38.566 --> 14:40.466
<i>There's still places here</i>

14:40.468 --> 14:43.136
<i>where no human
has ever set foot.</i>

15:30.317 --> 15:33.086
<i>I just love
that there's still places</i>

15:33.088 --> 15:37.156
<i>in the world you can go
to experience absolute silence.</i>

15:37.424 --> 15:40.126
When you're out here
and there's no wind

15:40.128 --> 15:42.762
your ears are just
straining to hear something...

15:42.764 --> 15:44.330
anything.

15:44.332 --> 15:45.665
You just don't realize

15:45.667 --> 15:47.733
how much noise
pollution there is

15:47.735 --> 15:50.736
in your daily life
back in the real world.

15:57.478 --> 16:00.413
One very important
thing when you're...

16:00.415 --> 16:02.181
working in the deep field is...

16:02.183 --> 16:05.785
to make sure never
to confuse your pee bottle

16:05.787 --> 16:07.587
with your water bottle.

16:20.801 --> 16:22.902
Well...

16:22.904 --> 16:24.904
the summit of Erebus

16:24.906 --> 16:27.540
and an ice fumarole
that's growing

16:27.542 --> 16:31.144
from steam coming out
of one of the cracks here.

16:35.716 --> 16:37.416
<i>Most days</i>

16:37.418 --> 16:39.619
<i>I can't believe I get
to work in this place.</i>

16:45.325 --> 16:47.226
<i>But there are days when I think</i>

16:47.228 --> 16:49.262
<i>they just can't pay me enough.</i>

16:57.372 --> 17:00.507
God, this is an awful place.

17:02.377 --> 17:05.712
In theory there should be
a flag right about there.

17:09.450 --> 17:10.717
Ah yeah, there we go.

17:14.321 --> 17:16.356
Gotta love GPSs.

17:22.896 --> 17:24.498
It's the middle of summer

17:24.500 --> 17:26.500
and if we check the time
it's ah...

17:26.502 --> 17:28.402
just after 12 o'clock.

17:28.404 --> 17:30.437
That's 12 o'clock
midnight though.

18:42.945 --> 18:45.012
Merry Christmas!

18:56.525 --> 18:57.791
Ah, Christmas dinner...

18:57.793 --> 19:00.627
making food
for lots and lots of people.

19:00.629 --> 19:01.728
It's a big day.

19:07.001 --> 19:09.403
We're spreading holiday cheer.

19:09.405 --> 19:12.606
<i>I think for a lot
of younger folks that come down</i>

19:12.608 --> 19:15.676
<i>it's a real good
experience for them.</i>

19:15.678 --> 19:20.047
<i>It's probably not a career
for most people,</i>

19:20.049 --> 19:22.582
but for some...
it is.

19:22.584 --> 19:25.820
I think I found it

19:25.921 --> 19:27.689
and kind of fell in love
with it.

19:48.345 --> 19:50.379
<i>I have been coming to Antarctica</i>

19:50.381 --> 19:52.715
<i>for about 13 years now.</i>

19:52.717 --> 19:54.383
<i>And when I came down
the first time</i>

19:54.385 --> 19:57.052
<i>I thought, "Ah yeah
this will be great to do once. "</i>

19:57.054 --> 19:58.454
<i>You know, just come
to Antarctica.</i>

19:58.456 --> 20:00.556
<i>And then I can say,
"Wow, I went to Antarctica. "</i>

20:00.558 --> 20:02.558
And then I signed on

20:02.560 --> 20:04.393
for a contract
the following year

20:04.395 --> 20:06.061
and then...
I don't know what happened.

20:06.063 --> 20:07.563
I'm still here.

20:17.006 --> 20:20.008
There's a saying among
the women of Antarctica

20:20.010 --> 20:22.044
<i>"The odds are good.</i>

20:22.046 --> 20:24.146
<i>But the goods, are odd. "</i>

20:28.785 --> 20:30.686
<i>Christine and I met down here</i>

20:30.688 --> 20:34.823
<i>and I proposed to her
in the winter of 2003.</i>

20:34.825 --> 20:37.760
<i>6 weeks later
we had an impromptu wedding</i>

20:37.762 --> 20:39.695
<i>down here on the ice.</i>

20:52.142 --> 20:55.711
<i>The flowers were all hand made
with folded paper.</i>

20:55.713 --> 20:57.112
<i>Christine's friend Lori</i>

20:57.114 --> 20:59.615
<i>made up a dress
from donated fabric.</i>

20:59.617 --> 21:01.950
<i>And the plumbers cut
us some rings</i>

21:01.952 --> 21:03.719
<i>made of brass.</i>

21:03.721 --> 21:06.455
<i>I borrowed the only
dinner jacket on base</i>

21:06.457 --> 21:08.490
<i>from Eric,
the station manager</i>

21:08.492 --> 21:10.692
<i>who then acted as our celebrant.</i>

21:14.063 --> 21:16.799
On this night here
on Ross Island,

21:16.801 --> 21:19.067
Christine Marie Gamble

21:19.069 --> 21:20.969
and Anthony Brendan Powell

21:20.971 --> 21:22.604
are celebrating their love

21:22.606 --> 21:24.006
and commitment
to each other.

21:24.008 --> 21:25.941
And tonight they will join

21:25.943 --> 21:27.676
as husband and wife

21:27.678 --> 21:31.213
in heart, body and soul.

21:31.215 --> 21:35.951
Hi, Dad!

21:35.953 --> 21:37.953
Just fine. Go ahead.

21:43.194 --> 21:44.493
I'm here.

21:51.502 --> 21:52.635
Thank you.

22:09.721 --> 22:12.689
<i>I've wintered over here
nine times now</i>

22:12.691 --> 22:15.058
<i>and Christine has
wintered eight times</i>

22:15.060 --> 22:16.860
<i>Living on the ice
is just something</i>

22:16.862 --> 22:19.729
<i>that's become so ingrained
in both of us.</i>

24:38.670 --> 24:40.904
<i>The TV version of penguins</i>

24:40.906 --> 24:43.040
<i>doesn't prepare you
for the reality</i>

24:43.042 --> 24:45.309
<i>of seeing an actual
penguin colony.</i>

24:47.278 --> 24:48.879
<i>There are thousands</i>

24:48.881 --> 24:51.248
<i>of frozen penguin corpses
that litter the ground.</i>

24:58.723 --> 25:02.693
<i>And in summer the sewer stench
from 100.000 penguins</i>

25:02.695 --> 25:04.396
<i>can be pretty unbearable.</i>

25:40.132 --> 25:43.368
Ten... nine... eight...

25:43.370 --> 25:47.205
Seven... Six...
Five... Four...

25:47.207 --> 25:50.308
Three... Two... One...

25:50.310 --> 25:52.911
Happy New Year, McMurdo!

26:09.161 --> 26:11.362
<i>I like this place
for a lot of reasons</i>

26:11.364 --> 26:13.398
<i>Part of me feels
like living at McMurdo</i>

26:13.400 --> 26:15.400
<i>is like living
in Never-never Land.</i>

26:16.435 --> 26:17.802
<i>There's a lot of people</i>

26:21.407 --> 26:22.841
<i>they have gone in a very</i>

26:22.843 --> 26:24.209
<i>different path in their lives.</i>

26:24.211 --> 26:26.911
<i>And sometimes one of the things
I like the best</i>

26:26.913 --> 26:27.912
<i>is being able to live a life</i>

26:27.914 --> 26:30.482
<i>with people who are
willing to take</i>

26:30.484 --> 26:31.850
<i>a slightly different path
different path in life.</i>

26:31.852 --> 26:33.151
And so for the first time
in my life

26:33.153 --> 26:36.020
I'm part of a majority because
a lot of us feel that way.

26:36.022 --> 26:38.156
And I've never been part
of the majority before.

26:46.366 --> 26:48.100
<i>We're in this...
we're in a box.</i>

26:48.102 --> 26:49.902
<i>And there's no escape
from each other.</i>

26:49.904 --> 26:51.137
<i>You can't get away.</i>

26:51.139 --> 26:54.340
<i>You're forced to interact
day in and day out.</i>

26:54.342 --> 26:57.143
<i>And you get to know people</i>

26:57.145 --> 27:00.045
very, very quickly.

27:00.047 --> 27:03.082
Whether those
relationships be good or bad

27:03.084 --> 27:05.184
they're going to be very,
very intense.

27:11.324 --> 27:13.392
That was awesome!

27:18.031 --> 27:20.199
<i>Okay, stand by
for contact again.</i>

28:29.603 --> 28:32.037
<i>McMurdo Sound is
as far south</i>

28:32.039 --> 28:35.507
<i>as it is possible to bring
a ship in the world.</i>

28:35.509 --> 28:37.509
<i>And the arrival
of the supply ship</i>

28:37.511 --> 28:40.079
<i>marks the last gasp
of summer here.</i>

29:33.100 --> 29:36.603
<i>Once the ship has been offloaded
it's immediately reloaded</i>

29:36.605 --> 29:39.572
<i>with all the rubbish,
recycling, human waste,</i>

29:39.574 --> 29:42.575
<i>and science-related cargo
from the last year.</i>

29:45.646 --> 29:47.647
<i>Nothing is left behind.</i>

29:58.025 --> 30:01.061
<i>At the end of February,
the sun starts to briefly</i>

30:01.063 --> 30:03.029
<i>dip back below the horizon.</i>

